A [guided missile](/Guided_missile) equipped with precise [targeting capabilities](/Targeting_(warfare)) and adaptable to a multitude of [launch platforms](/Launch_platform) represents a significant evolution in modern [military technology](/Military_technology).

For any missile that adheres to a primarily [ballistic trajectory](/Ballistic_trajectory), one should refer to the distinct classification of a [Ballistic missile](/Ballistic_missile).

---

A [BGM-109 Tomahawk](/Tomahawk_(missile_family)) slicing through the air in November 2002. A rather predictable display, given its design.

A [cruise missile](/Cruise_missile) is, at its core, an [unmanned](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle) and [self-propelled](/Self-propelled) [guided missile](/Guided_missile) that maintains its flight through the generation of [aerodynamic lift](/Aerodynamic_lift) for the predominant portion of its operational journey. These intricate machines are meticulously engineered to deliver a substantial [payload](/Payload) — often a formidable [warhead](/Warhead) — across considerable distances with an unnerving degree of [precision](/Precision_strike_munition). Contemporary cruise missile designs are capable of traversing skies at impressive velocities, ranging from high [subsonic](/Aerodynamics) speeds, through the disruptive forces of [supersonic](/Supersonic) travel, and even venturing into the nascent, extreme realm of [hypersonic](/Hypersonic) flight. They are inherently [self-navigating](/Navigation_system), equipped with advanced systems that allow them to follow a non-[ballistic](/Ballistics), often serpentine, and invariably an extremely low-altitude flight path, a design choice that makes them notoriously difficult to detect and intercept. This characteristic, as noted in various analyses, is fundamental to their effectiveness in modern conflict scenarios. &#91;1&#93;

### History

The notion of an "aerial torpedo" — essentially a precursor to the modern cruise missile — made an early, rather imaginative appearance in the 1909 British silent film, [The Airship Destroyer](/The_Airship_Destroyer). This cinematic vision depicted wirelessly controlled flying torpedoes being deployed with the specific intent of obliterating [airships](/Airship) that were, in the film's narrative, engaged in the rather unsportsmanlike activity of bombing [London](/London). &#91;2&#93; It seems humanity has always had a knack for dreaming up sophisticated ways to destroy things from afar.

The actual, albeit rudimentary, development of such concepts began to manifest in the real world in 1916. It was then that the American aviator and inventor, [Lawrence Sperry](/Lawrence_Sperry), meticulously constructed and subsequently patented his own iteration of an "aerial torpedo." This device, known as the [Hewitt-Sperry Automatic Airplane](/Hewitt-Sperry_Automatic_Airplane), was a compact [biplane](/Biplane) airframe specifically designed to carry a potent [TNT](/TNT) explosive charge. Its guidance system was remarkably advanced for its time, incorporating a Sperry [autopilot](/Autopilot) coupled with a barometric altitude control mechanism, allowing for a degree of automated flight. The pioneering work of Sperry and his contemporaries served as a significant inspiration. In response, the [United States Army](/United_States_Army) embarked on its own program, developing a similar flying bomb, famously dubbed the [Kettering Bug](/Kettering_Bug). Not to be outdone, Germany also conducted trials with their own remote-controlled aerial gliders, referred to as [Torpedogleiter](/Siemens_torpedo_glider), constructed by the industrial giant [Siemens-Schuckert](/Siemens-Schuckert), with these experiments commencing as early as 1916. &#91;3&#93;

During the often-overlooked [Interwar Period](/Interwar_Period), the British [Royal Aircraft Establishment](/Royal_Aircraft_Establishment) dedicated resources to the development of the [Larynx (Long Range Gun with Lynx Engine)](/Larynx_(Long_Range_Gun_with_Lynx_Engine)). This early cruise missile prototype underwent a limited series of flight tests throughout the 1920s, demonstrating continued interest in the concept, even if the technology wasn't quite ready for prime time. &#91;4&#93;

The [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) also entered the fray, with the renowned rocket engineer [Sergei Korolev](/Sergei_Korolev) at the helm of the [GIRD](/GIRD)-06 cruise missile project. Active from 1932 to 1939, this ambitious undertaking explored a novel rocket-powered boost-[glide bomb](/Glide_bomb) design. The 06/III (RP-216) and 06/IV (RP-212) variants were notably equipped with [gyroscopic](/Gyroscopic) guidance systems, a testament to the early ambition for precision. &#91;5&#93; The theoretical design aimed for the vehicle to boost to an impressive 28&#160;km (17&#160;mi) altitude and then glide for a considerable distance of 280&#160;km (170&#160;mi). However, the harsh realities of early rocketry meant that test flights conducted in 1934 and 1936 only managed to achieve a modest altitude of 500 metres (1,600&#160;ft). A rather stark reminder that aspiration often outpaces capability in the early stages of any technology.

The concept truly materialized as an operational weapon during [World War II](/World_War_II). In 1944, [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany), in its relentless pursuit of technological advantage, unleashed the first operational cruise missiles upon the world. The infamous [V-1](/V-1_flying_bomb), frequently referred to simply as a [flying bomb](/Flying_bomb), incorporated a reliable gyroscope guidance system. Its propulsion came from a rudimentary, yet effective, [pulsejet](/Pulsejet) engine, the distinctive, unsettling sound of which earned it the chilling nicknames "buzz bomb" or "doodlebug" among those who endured its unpredictable arrival. &#91;6&#93; The accuracy of the V-1 was, by modern standards, rather crude, sufficient only for engagement against very large, indiscriminate targets, typically the general area of an entire city. Its operational range of 250&#160;km (160&#160;mi) was also significantly less than what a conventional [bomber](/Bomber) could achieve carrying a comparable payload. The V-1's primary advantages, however, lay in its speed—though not quite fast enough to consistently outpace the propeller-driven [interceptors](/Interceptor) of the era—and, crucially, its expendability. The production cost of a V-1 was a mere fraction of that of the more complex [V-2](/V-2) [supersonic](/Supersonic) [ballistic missile](/Ballistic_missile), despite carrying a similarly sized [warhead](/Warhead). &#91;7&#93; A grim testament to the efficiency of mass-produced destruction. Unlike the V-2, the initial deployments of the V-1 necessitated stationary launch ramps, which, as one might expect, proved highly vulnerable to concentrated bombardment by Allied forces. &#91;8&#93;

Concurrently, in 1943, Nazi Germany also ventured into the development of the [Mistel](/Mistel) [composite aircraft](/Composite_aircraft) program. This ingenious, if somewhat desperate, concept can be viewed as an early, rudimentary form of an [air-launched cruise missile](/Air-launched_cruise_missile). It involved a piloted [fighter-type aircraft](/Fighter_aircraft) mounted atop an unpiloted, larger [bomber-sized aircraft](/Bomber) that was packed to the brim with explosives. The piloted fighter would guide the combined monstrosity towards its target, releasing the explosive-laden bomber as it approached. Near the very end of the war, bomber-launched variants of the V-1 saw limited operational service, a clear indication of the weapon's perceived utility. The pioneering V-1's design was even reverse-engineered with remarkable speed by the Americans, resulting in the [Republic-Ford JB-2](/Republic-Ford_JB-2) cruise missile. &#91;9&#93; Because, of course, a good idea for destruction is always worth copying.

In the immediate aftermath of [World War II](/World_War_II), the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) found itself overseeing a rather sprawling portfolio of 21 distinct [guided missile](/Guided_missile) projects, a number that included several proposed cruise missile designs. By 1948, the inevitable culling occurred, and all but four of these ambitious projects had been summarily canceled. The survivors included the [Air Materiel Command](/Air_Materiel_Command) Banshee, the [SM-62 Snark](/SM-62_Snark), the [SM-64 Navaho](/SM-64_Navaho), and the MGM-1 Matador. The Banshee, unfortunately, proved to be a design conceptually similar to the ill-fated [Operation Aphrodite](/Operation_Aphrodite) (where manned bombers were turned into flying bombs), and like its predecessor, it failed to meet expectations and was canceled in April 1949. &#91;10&#93; Simultaneously, the [US Navy](/US_Navy) initiated [Operation Bumblebee](/Operation_Bumblebee), a research and development program conducted at [Topsail Island](/Topsail_Island), [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), from approximately June 1, 1946, to July 28, 1948. While not directly producing an operational cruise missile itself, Bumblebee was instrumental in generating crucial proof-of-concept technologies that profoundly influenced subsequent US military missile projects, laying foundational groundwork for future guided weapons.

The tense standoff of the [Cold War](/Cold_War) spurred both the [United States](/United_States) and the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) to delve even deeper into the cruise missile concept. This era saw extensive experimentation and the eventual deployment of early cruise missiles from a diverse array of platforms: land-based launchers, formidable [submarines](/Submarine), and strategic [aircraft](/Aircraft). A significant outcome of the United States Navy's submarine missile project was the [SSM-N-8 Regulus](/SSM-N-8_Regulus) missile. This weapon drew clear conceptual lineage from the V-1, but crucially, it was powered by a more advanced [Allison J33](/Allison_J33) [jet engine](/Jet_engine). The Regulus did enter service, offering a novel offensive capability, but its tenure was ultimately cut short by the advent of [submarine launched ballistic missiles](/Submarine_launched_ballistic_missile) (SLBMs). SLBMs offered a distinct tactical advantage: they did not necessitate the submarine to surface, or even to guide the missile to its target after launch, thereby significantly reducing the submarine's vulnerability.

The [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force)'s first operational [surface-to-surface missile](/Surface-to-surface_missile) was the winged, mobile, and rather ominously [nuclear-capable](/Nuclear_weapon) [MGM-1 Matador](/MGM-1_Matador). This missile also shared conceptual similarities with the V-1, though it was significantly more sophisticated. Its overseas deployment commenced in 1954, with initial placements in [West Germany](/West_Germany), followed by later deployments to the [Republic of China](/Republic_of_China) (Taiwan) and [South Korea](/South_Korea). A particularly illustrative moment of its strategic importance occurred on November 7, 1956. In response to the grave crisis precipitated by the Soviet intervention in Hungary, which brutally suppressed the [Hungarian Revolution of 1956](/Hungarian_Revolution_of_1956), the U.S. Air Force deployed Matador units in West Germany. These missiles, capable of striking targets deep within the [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact) territories, were moved from their fixed day-to-day sites to unannounced, dispersed launch locations, a clear and unambiguous signal of readiness.

Between 1957 and 1961, the United States pursued an extraordinarily ambitious and generously funded program to develop a truly revolutionary [nuclear-powered cruise missile](/Nuclear_propulsion), known as the [Supersonic Low Altitude Missile](/Supersonic_Low_Altitude_Missile) (SLAM). This audacious weapon was conceived to fly beneath the enemy's [radar](/Radar) detection thresholds at sustained speeds exceeding [Mach](/Mach) 3. Its intended mission was to carry multiple [hydrogen bombs](/Hydrogen_bombs) and drop them sequentially along its flight path over enemy territory, effectively creating a prolonged, devastating nuclear strike. While the underlying concept was rigorously tested and proven sound, and its immense 500-megawatt (670,000&#160;hp) engine successfully completed a test run in 1961, an airworthy device was, perhaps fortunately, never fully completed. The project was ultimately abandoned in favor of the more strategically viable and less environmentally catastrophic development of [Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles](/ICBM).

While [ballistic missiles](/Ballistic_missile) emerged as the preferred weapons for striking fixed land targets due to their speed and trajectory, large, [nuclear](/Nuclear_weapon) and [conventional weapon](/Conventional_weapon)-tipped cruise missiles were concurrently viewed by the [USSR](/Soviet_Union) as a primary means to neutralize the formidable [United States naval](/United_States_Navy) [carrier battle groups](/Carrier_battle_group). To facilitate this strategic objective, specialized large [submarines](/Submarine) (such as the [Echo](/Echo-class_submarine) and [Oscar](/Oscar-class_submarine) classes) were designed and constructed specifically to carry these potent weapons and discreetly shadow United States battle groups at sea. In parallel, heavy [bombers](/Bomber) (including the iconic [Backfire](/Tupolev_Tu-22M), [Bear](/Tupolev_Tu-95), and [Blackjack](/Tupolev_Tu-160) models) were extensively modified and equipped to deploy these weapons in their [air-launched cruise missile](/Air-launched_cruise_missile) (ALCM) configurations, underscoring the versatility and perceived threat of this weapon class across multiple domains.

### Categories

Cruise missiles, in their diverse manifestations, can be systematically categorized based on several critical parameters: the size of their [payload](/Payload) or [warhead](/Warhead), their operational [speed](/Speed), their effective [range](/Range_(firearms)), and the specific [platform](/Launch_platform) from which they are launched. It is a common practice in modern defense industries to produce variants of the same core missile design, adapting them for deployment from different launch platforms. A prime example of this adaptability can be seen in the development of both air-launched and submarine-launched versions derived from a single missile family.

The sophistication of [guidance systems](/Missile_guidance) can also vary considerably across different missile types. Some advanced missiles offer the flexibility of being fitted with a selection of navigation systems, allowing for mission-specific tailoring. These can include traditional [Inertial navigation systems](/Inertial_navigation), advanced [TERCOM](/TERCOM) (Terrain Contour Matching) systems, or the ubiquitous precision offered by [satellite navigation](/Satellite_navigation). Furthermore, larger cruise missiles typically possess the capacity to carry either a conventional explosive warhead or a devastating nuclear warhead, granting them dual-use strategic flexibility. Smaller cruise missiles, constrained by their physical dimensions and design parameters, are generally limited to carrying only conventional warheads, serving a more tactical role.

#### Hypersonic

• See also: [Hypersonic weapon](/Hypersonic_weapon) and [Hypersonic flight](/Hypersonic_flight)

A [hypersonic](/Hypersonic) cruise missile is defined by its ability to travel at speeds of at least five times the [speed of sound](/Speed_of_sound) – a staggering [Mach](/Mach) 5 or greater. This extreme velocity presents not only formidable engineering challenges but also fundamentally alters the dynamics of warfare, drastically compressing decision-making timelines for defenders. The pursuit of hypersonic capabilities is a key area of global arms competition, as these weapons offer unparalleled speed and maneuverability, making them incredibly difficult to intercept with current defense systems.

Examples of these cutting-edge, often still developmental, systems include:

• The [3M22 Zircon](/3M22_Zircon) is a Russian [hypersonic](/Hypersonic_weapons) [anti-ship](/Anti-ship_missile) cruise missile, reportedly capable of ranges between >1000–1500&#160;km. Its existence, and claimed capabilities, have certainly raised a few eyebrows in naval circles. &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;14&#93;

• The [ASN4G](/ASN4G) (Air-Sol Nucléaire de 4e Génération) is a [scramjet](/Scramjet)-powered hypersonic cruise missile currently under development by France, intended to bolster its strategic deterrent. &#91;15&#93; &#91;16&#93;

• [BrahMos-II](/BrahMos-II) is a hypersonic cruise missile with an anticipated range of ≈800–1500&#160;km. This joint Indian and Russian project has been under development since at least 2011 &#91;update&#93; and is a testament to shared ambitions in advanced missile technology. &#91;17&#93; &#91;14&#93; &#91;18&#93; &#91;19&#93;

• The [CJ-1000](/CJ-1000_(missile)) is a Chinese [hypersonic](/Hypersonic) [scramjet](/Scramjet) [anti-ship](/Anti-ship_missile)/[land-attack](/Land-attack_missile) cruise missile, indicating a clear focus on both naval and terrestrial threats. &#91;20&#93; &#91;21&#93;

• Hycore is a South Korean hypersonic missile project. &#91;22&#93;

• The [HSTDV](/HSTDV) (Hypersonic Technology Demonstrator Vehicle) is a [hypersonic](/Hypersonic) [scramjet](/Scramjet) demonstrator. It serves as a carrier vehicle for future hypersonic long-range cruise missiles, a project being actively developed by India's [Defence Research and Development Organisation](/Defence_Research_and_Development_Organisation) (DRDO). &#91;23&#93; &#91;24&#93;

• The [ET-LDHCM](/ET-LDHCM) is a long-range hypersonic cruise missile also under development by the [DRDO](/DRDO), indicating a serious commitment to this domain. &#91;25&#93; &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93;

• Hyfly-2, a hypersonic [air-launched cruise missile](/Air-launched_cruise_missile), made its public debut at Sea Air Space 2021. This system is being developed by the aerospace giant [Boeing](/Boeing). &#91;28&#93;

• The [Hypersonic Air-breathing Weapon Concept](/Hypersonic_Air-breathing_Weapon_Concept) (HAWC, pronounced Hawk) is a [scramjet](/Scramjet)-powered hypersonic [air-launched cruise missile](/Air-launched_cruise_missile) that, rather surprisingly, operates without a conventional [warhead](/Warhead). Instead, it relies on its immense [kinetic energy](/Kinetic_energy) upon impact to destroy its target. This innovative approach is being developed by [DARPA](/DARPA). &#91;29&#93; &#91;30&#93;

• The [Hypersonic Air Launched Offensive Anti-Surface](/Hypersonic_Air_Launched_Offensive_Anti-Surface) (HALO) is an [air-launched](/Air-launched_cruise_missile) [anti-ship missile](/Anti-ship_missile) being developed under the Offensive Anti-Surface Warfare Increment 2 (OASuW Inc 2) program for the [US Navy](/US_Navy). &#91;31&#93; &#91;32&#93;

• The [Hypersonic Attack Cruise Missile](/Hypersonic_Attack_Cruise_Missile) (HACM) is a planned system intended for future use by the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force). &#91;33&#93; &#91;34&#93;

• [SCIFiRE](/SCIFiRE) (Southern Cross Integrated Flight Research Experiment) is a joint program between the [US Department of Defense](/US_Department_of_Defense) and the Australian [Department of Defence](/Department_of_Defence_(Australia)) focused on developing a Mach 5 [scramjet](/Scramjet)-powered missile. In September 2021, the US Department of Defense awarded [Preliminary Design Review](/Preliminary_Design_Review) contracts for this ambitious project to prominent defense contractors [Boeing](/Boeing), [Lockheed Martin](/Lockheed_Martin), and [Raytheon Missiles & Defense](/Raytheon_Missiles_%26_Defense). &#91;35&#93; &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93; &#91;38&#93; &#91;39&#93;

• The [YJ-19](/YJ-19) is another Chinese [hypersonic](/Hypersonic) [scramjet](/Scramjet) [anti-ship](/Anti-ship_missile) cruise missile, demonstrating the country's multi-pronged approach to hypersonic weapons development. &#91;40&#93; &#91;41&#93;

#### Supersonic

The [BrahMos](/BrahMos) missile, as showcased at IMDS 2007.

These missiles are characterized by their ability to achieve speeds exceeding the [speed of sound](/Speed_of_sound), typically employing advanced [ramjet](/Ramjet) engines for propulsion. Their operational range generally falls within 100–500&#160;km, though some variants can achieve significantly greater distances. The [guidance systems](/Missile_guidance) employed across this category are diverse, tailored to specific mission requirements and target types. The tactical advantage of supersonic speed lies in reducing the time available for enemy reaction and interception, making them highly effective against both static and moving targets.

Examples of prominent supersonic cruise missiles include:

• [ASALM](/ASALM): A US [ALCM](/Air-launched_cruise_missile) prototype that was successfully test-flown to an impressive hypersonic Mach 5.5, pushing the boundaries of what was considered achievable.

• [3M-54 Kalibr](/3M-54_Kalibr): A versatile Russian missile with a substantial range of up to 4,500&#160;km and a top speed of Mach 3. It's worth noting that the "Sizzler" variant of the Kalibr is specifically designed to achieve supersonic speed only during its terminal, most critical, stage of flight.

• [3M-51 Alfa](/3M-51_Alfa): Another Russian design, with a range of 250&#160;km and a speed of Mach 2.5.

• [Air-Sol Moyenne Portée](/Air-Sol_Moyenne_Port%C3%A9e): A French supersonic [stand-off](/Standoff_missile) nuclear missile, boasting a range of 300–500&#160;km+, designed for strategic deterrence. &#160;

• [ASM-3](/ASM-3): A Japanese missile with a range of 400&#160;km and speeds exceeding Mach 3.

• [BrahMos](/BrahMos): A joint Indian/Russian venture, this missile has a range of 290–800&#160;km and can reach speeds of Mach 3, making it a formidable weapon. &#91;42&#93;

• Blyskavka: A Ukrainian missile developed by Artem Luch and [Pivdenmash](/Pivdenmash), with a range of 100–370&#160;km. &#160;

• [CX-1](/CX-1_Missile_Systems): A Chinese missile with a range of 280&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.

• [CJ-100 / DF-100](/DF-100): A Chinese missile with an extended range of 2000–3000&#160;km and a reported speed of Mach 5.

• [FC/ASW](/FC/ASW): A transnational cruise missile program involving France, Germany, and the UK, currently under development. &#91;43&#93; &#91;44&#93; &#91;45&#93; &#91;46&#93; &#91;47&#93;

• [Hsiung Feng III](/Hsiung_Feng_III): A Taiwanese missile with a range of 100–150&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.5.

• [Hyunmoo-3](/Hyunmoo-3): A South Korean missile with a significant range of 1500&#160;km and a speed of Mach 1.2.

• [Kh-20](/Kh-20): A Soviet-era missile with a range of 380–600&#160;km and a speed of Mach 2.

• [Kh-31](/Kh-31): A versatile Russian missile with a range of 25–110&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.5.

• [Kh-32](/Kh-32): A Russian missile with a range of 600–1,000&#160;km and an impressive speed of Mach 4.6.

• [Kh-80](/Kh-80): A Russian missile boasting an intercontinental range of 3,000–5,000&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.

• [P-270 Moskit](/P-270_Moskit): A Russian/Soviet anti-ship missile with a range of 120–250&#160;km and speeds between Mach 2–3.

• [P-500 Bazalt](/P-500_Bazalt): A Soviet anti-ship missile with a range of 550&#160;km and speeds exceeding Mach 3.

• [P-700 Granit](/P-700_Granit): Another large Soviet anti-ship missile, with a range of 625&#160;km and speeds above Mach 2.5.

• [P-800 Oniks / Kh-61](/P-800_Oniks): A Russian/Soviet anti-ship and land-attack missile with a range of 600–800&#160;km and a speed of Mach 2.6.

• [P-1000 Vulkan](/P-1000_Vulkan): A powerful Russian anti-ship missile with a range of 800&#160;km and speeds exceeding Mach 3.

• [YJ-12](/YJ-12): A Chinese anti-ship missile with a range of 250–400&#160;km and a speed of Mach 4.

• [YJ-18](/YJ-18): A Chinese anti-ship missile with a range of 220–540&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.

• [YJ-91](/YJ-91): A Chinese anti-radiation/anti-ship missile with a range of 15–120&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.5.

• [Yun Feng](/Yun_Feng): A Taiwanese missile with a substantial range of 1200–2,000&#160;km and a speed of Mach 3.

• [SSM-N-9 Regulus II](/SSM-N-9_Regulus_II): An American missile with a range of 1,852&#160;km and a speed of Mach 2.

#### Intercontinental-range supersonic

These are designs that aimed for truly global reach at supersonic speeds, though many were ultimately canceled due to technological hurdles or strategic shifts towards [ICBMs](/ICBMs). A testament to ambitious thinking that sometimes outstrips practicality.

• [Burya](/Burya): A Soviet project with an intended range of 8,500&#160;km, canceled in 1960.

• [MKR](/MKR_(missile)): Another Soviet design, with an impressive range of 8,000&#160;km.

• [RSS-40 Buran](/RSS-40_Buran): A Soviet project with a range of 8,500&#160;km, canceled in 1957.

• [SLAM](/Supersonic_Low_Altitude_Missile): The American nuclear-powered cruise missile, canceled in 1964.

• [SM-64 Navaho](/SM-64_Navaho): An American project, canceled in 1958.

#### Long-range subsonic

India's [Nirbhay](/Nirbhay) missiles, conspicuously mounted on a truck-based launcher.

Several nations, including China, France, India, Iran, Israel, Japan, North Korea, Russia, South Korea, Ukraine, and the United States, have successfully developed and deployed a range of long-range subsonic cruise missiles. These weapons are characterized by their considerable operational reach, typically exceeding 1,000 kilometres (620&#160;mi), and their cruising speed, which hovers around 800 kilometres per hour (500&#160;mph). &#91;48&#93; Such missiles generally possess a launch weight of approximately 1,500 kilograms (3,300&#160;lb) &#91;49&#93; and are versatile enough to carry either a conventional high-explosive warhead or a strategic nuclear warhead. Earlier generations of these missiles primarily relied on [inertial navigation](/Inertial_navigation) for guidance. However, subsequent versions have incorporated significantly more accurate systems such as [TERCOM](/TERCOM) (Terrain Contour Matching) and [DSMAC](/TERCOM) (Digital Scene-Matching Area Correlator), which enhance precision by comparing real-time sensor data with stored terrain maps or digital imagery. The most recent and advanced iterations of these missiles now frequently integrate [satellite navigation](/Satellite_navigation) (e.g., GPS, GLONASS) for unparalleled accuracy.

Examples of these workhorses of modern missile arsenals include:

• [3M-54 Kalibr](/3M-54_Kalibr): A highly adaptable Russian missile with an impressive maximum range of up to 4,500&#160;km, capable of both anti-ship and land-attack roles.

• [AGM-86 ALCM](/AGM-86_ALCM): The American [Air-Launched Cruise Missile](/Air-launched_cruise_missile), with variants ranging from 1,100 to over 2,400&#160;km, a staple of strategic bomber fleets.

• [AGM-129 ACM](/AGM-129_ACM): The American [Advanced Cruise Missile](/AGM-129_ACM), designed for stealth and long-range penetration, with a range between 3,450 to 3,700&#160;km.

• [AGM-181 LRSO](/AGM-181_LRSO): The American Long-Range Standoff weapon, a next-generation cruise missile with a range exceeding 2,500&#160;km.

• [BGM-109 Tomahawk](/BGM-109_Tomahawk): Perhaps the most iconic cruise missile, renowned for its accuracy and versatility, with a range of up to 1,700&#160;km.

• [BGM-109G Ground Launched Cruise Missile](/BGM-109G_Ground_Launched_Cruise_Missile): A land-based variant of the Tomahawk, capable of 2,500&#160;km, though now out of service due to arms treaties.

• [Kh-55](/Kh-55) and Kh-65: Russian strategic cruise missiles, with the Kh-55 boasting a range of 3,000&#160;km.

• [Kh-101](/Kh-101): A modern Russian strategic cruise missile with an extended range of 4,500–5,500&#160;km, featuring stealth characteristics.

• [Iskander-K](/Iskander-K): A Russian tactical missile system, with a cruise missile variant capable of ranges not less than 3,500&#160;km.

• [Hwasal-2](/Hwasal-2): A North Korean cruise missile, reported to have a range exceeding 2,000&#160;km.

• [RK-55](/RK-55): A Soviet-era strategic cruise missile with a range of 3,000&#160;km.

• [Nirbhay](/Nirbhay): India's indigenous long-range subsonic cruise missile, with a range of up to 1,500&#160;km. &#91;50&#93;

• [MdCN](/MdCN): The French *Missile de Croisière Naval* (Naval Cruise Missile), with a range of up to 1,400&#160;km.

• [Paveh](/Paveh_cruise_missile): An Iranian cruise missile, claimed to have a range of 1,650&#160;km. &#91;51&#93;

• [Hoveyzeh](/Hoveyzeh_(cruise_missile)): Another Iranian cruise missile, with a claimed range of 1,350&#160;km. &#91;52&#93;

• [Abu Mahdi](/Abu_Mahdi_(missile)): An Iranian missile, reported to have a range exceeding 1,000&#160;km. &#91;53&#93;

• [Quds 1](/Quds_1): A Houthi-developed cruise missile.

• [Hsiung Feng IIE](/Hsiung_Feng_IIE): A Taiwanese cruise missile with a range of 600–1,200&#160;km.

